0.0.0.1 Phase one: Ingest

# load data and view data
data <- read.csv("/Users/lyndon//COVID vaccine//202104 /STM/5-.csv")

# CAUTION: the default settings of the function
# otherwise, you cannot obtain all documents in the future steps
# ?textProcessor
# we have pre-processed the corpus in the Python env
processed <- textProcessor(data$documents, 
                           metadata=data, 
                           lowercase=FALSE, 
                           removestopwords=FALSE, 
                           removenumbers=FALSE, 
                           removepunctuation=FALSE, 
                           stem=FALSE, 
                           wordLengths=c(1, Inf), 
                           language="na")
Building corpus... 
Creating Output... 
length(processed$documents)
[1] 764
# prepare documents for analysis with STM
# ?prepDocuments
# documents: list, contains word indices and their associated counts
# vocab: vector, contains the words associated with their word indices
# metadata: matrix, containing document covs
out <- prepDocuments(processed$documents, 
                     processed$vocab, 
                     processed$meta, 
                     lower.thresh=1) 
Removing 5196 of 8691 terms (5196 of 31829 tokens) due to frequency 
Removing 1 Documents with No Words 
Your corpus now has 763 documents, 3495 terms and 26633 tokens.
# lower.thresh and upper.thresh all denote the number of documents, not the number of words
# the default value of lower.thresh is 1
docs <- out$documents
vocab <- out$vocab
meta <- out$meta
# docs is a list
print(length(docs))

0.0.0.2 Phase two: Prepare

# how many words and documents will be removed from the data at each word threshold?
# I prefer to keep as many documents as possible
plotRemoved(processed$documents, 
            lower.thresh=seq(1, dim(data)[1] * .5, by=5))

0.0.0.3 Phase three: Evaluate

# ?searchK
# this code snippet consumes a long time
# adopt a **data-driven approach** to determine the number of topics
storage <- searchK(docs, 
                   vocab, 
                   K=c(seq(2, 10, 1)), # K = a range of topic numbers
                   prevalence=~userType, 
                   data=meta, 
                   init.type="Spectral", 
                   cores=4, 
                   verbose=FALSE)
Using multiple-cores.  Progress will not be shown. 
K=2 is equivalent to a unidimensional scaling model which you may prefer.
# according to the semantic coherence and residuals fluctuation, select K = 4
plot(storage)

0.0.0.4 Phase four: Estimate

  • Allow the observed metadata to affect the frequency with which a topic is discussed
# estimate the STM
vaxFit <- stm(documents=docs, 
              vocab=vocab, 
              K=3, 
              prevalence=~userType, 
              max.em.its=75, 
              data=meta, 
              init.type="Spectral", 
              seed=12345, 
              verbose=FALSE)

0.0.0.5 Phase five: Understand

  • Interpret the STM by plotting and inspecting results
# ?labelTopics
# label the topics
# FREX: weights words by their overall frequency and how exclusive they are to the topic
# Lift: weights words by dividing by their frequency in other topics, give higher weight to words that appear less frequently in other topics
# Score: divides the log frequency of the word in the topic by the log frequency of the word in other topics
labelTopics(vaxFit, 
            topics=c(1, 2, 3), 
            n=30)

# core part: how prevalence of topics varies across documents according to document covs/metadata
out$meta$userType <- as.factor(out$meta$userType)
prep <- estimateEffect(1:3 ~ userType, 
                       vaxFit, 
                       meta=out$meta, 
                       uncertainty="Global")
summary(prep, 
        topics=c(1, 2, 3))

     covariate="userType",

     model=vaxFit, 
     method="difference", 
     cov.value1="laypeople",
